===Tay–Sachs disease===
[[Tay–Sachs disease]], a fatal illness of children that causes mental deterioration prior to death, was historically more prevalent among [[Ashkenazi Jews]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ninds.nih.gov/disorders/taysachs/taysachs.htm 
|title=Tay–Sachs Disease Information Page |publisher=[[National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke]] |date=February 14, 2007 |accessdate=May 25, 2008}}</ref> although high levels of the disease are also found in some Pennsylvania Dutch, Southern Louisiana Cajun and Eastern Quebec French Canadian populations.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0889-8545(01)00002-X |author=Sutton VR |title=Tay–Sachs disease screening and counseling families at risk for metabolic disease |journal=Obstet. Gynecol. Clin. North Am. |volume=29 |issue=2 |pages=287–96 |year=2002 |month=June |pmid=12108829}}</ref> Since the 1970s, however, proactive genetic testing has been quite effective in eliminating Tay–Sachs from the Ashkenazi Jewish population.<ref name="genomenewsnetwork">{{cite web | publisher=Genome News Network, J. Craig Venter Institute | title=The Success Story of Gene Tests | first=Julie | last=Buckles | date= August 20, 2001 | accessdate = April 14, 2008 | url = http://www.genomenewsnetwork.org/articles/08_01/Tay_Sachs_gene_tests.shtml}}</ref>

===Lipid transport diseases===

[[Gaucher's disease]], in which [[lipid]]s accumulate in inappropriate locations, occurs most frequently among Ashkenazi Jews;<ref>{{cite journal |author=Diaz GA, Gelb BD, Risch N, ''et al.'' |title=Gaucher disease: the origins of the Ashkenazi Jewish N370S and 84GG acid beta-glucosidase mutations |journal=Am. J. Hum. Genet. |volume=66 |issue=6 |pages=1821–32 |year=2000 |pmid=10777718 |pmc=1378046|doi=10.1086/302946}}'</ref> the disease is carried by roughly 1 in every 15 Ashkenazi Jews, compared to 1 in 100 of the general American population.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gaucherdisease.org/prevalence.php |title=National Gaucher Foundation |accessdate=May 30, 2007}}</ref> Gaucher's disease can cause [[brain damage]] and [[seizure]]s, but these effects are not usually present in the form manifested among Ashkenazi Jews; while sufferers still bruise easily, and it can still potentially rupture the [[spleen]], it generally has only a minor impact on life expectancy.

Ashkenazi Jews are also highly affected by other [[lysosomal storage disease]]s, particularly in the form of [[lipid storage disorder]]s. Compared to other ethnic groups, they more frequently act as carriers of [[mucolipidosis]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mssm.edu/jewish_genetics/diseases/mucolipidosis.shtml |title=Mount Sinai – Center for Jewish Genetic Diseases – Department of Human Genetics |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Niemann–Pick disease]],<ref>[http://www.jewishgeneticscenter.org/what/ashkenazi/niemann.asp Ashkenazi Disorders: Mendelian – Niemann–Pick disease: from The Chicago Center for Jewish Genetic Disorders]</ref> the latter of which can prove fatal.

The occurrence of several lysosomal storage disorders in the same population suggests that the alleles responsible might have conferred some [[selection|selective advantage]] in the past.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Boas FE |title=Linkage to Gaucher mutations in the Ashkenazi population: effect of drift on decay of linkage disequilibrium and evidence for heterozygote selection |journal=Blood Cells Mol. Dis. |volume=26 |issue=4 |pages=348–59 |year=2000 |month=August |pmid=11042036 |doi=10.1006/bcmd.2000.0314}}</ref> This would be similar to the [[hemoglobin]] allele which is responsible for [[sickle-cell disease]], but solely in people with two copies; those with just one copy of the allele have a [[sickle cell trait]] and gain partial immunity to [[malaria]] as a result. This effect is called [[heterozygote advantage]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Harpending H, Cochran G |title=Genetic diversity and genetic burden in humans |journal=Infect. Genet. Evol. |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=154–62 |year=2006 |month=March |pmid=16246638 |doi=10.1016/j.meegid.2005.04.002}}</ref> 

It has been proposed that some of these disorders became common in this population due to selection for high levels of [[intelligence]] (see [[Ashkenazi intelligence]]).<ref name="Wade">{{Cite news |author=Nicholas Wade |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/03/science/03gene.html |title=Researchers Say Intelligence and Diseases May Be Linked in Ashkenazic Genes |work=The New York Times |date=June 3, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Cochran G, Hardy J, Harpending H |title=Natural history of Ashkenazi intelligence |journal=J Biosoc Sci |volume=38 |issue=5 |pages=659–93 |year=2006 |month=September |pmid=16867211 |doi=10.1017/S0021932005027069 |url=http://homepage.mac.com/harpend/.Public/AshkenaziIQ.jbiosocsci.pdf}}</ref> However, other research suggests that there is no difference between the frequency of this group of diseases and other genetic diseases in Ashkenazis, which is evidence against any specific selectivity towards lysosomal disorders.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Risch N, Tang H, Katzenstein H, Ekstein J |title=Geographic Distribution of Disease Mutations in the Ashkenazi Jewish Population Supports Genetic Drift over Selection |journal=Am. J. Hum. Genet. |volume=72 |issue=4 |pages=812–22 |year=2003 |month=April |pmid=12612865 |pmc=1180346 |doi=10.1086/373882}}</ref>

===Familial dysautonomia===

[[Familial dysautonomia]] (Riley–Day Syndrome), which causes [[vomiting]], speech problems, an inability to [[cry]], and false [[sensory perception]], is almost exclusive to Ashkenazi Jews;<ref>[http://www.jewishgeneticscenter.org/what/ashkenazi/familial.asp Ashkenazi Disorders: Mendelian – Familial dysautonomia: from The Chicago Center for Jewish Genetic Disorders]</ref> Ashkenazi Jews are almost 100 times more likely to carry the disease than anyone else.<ref>about 1 in 30 Ashkenazi Jews carry the disease, compared to 1 in 3000 of the general population</ref>

